    body: "The Corpus Christi procession is a solemn public procession of the Blessed Sacrament through the streets, held on or near the Solemnity of the Most Holy Body and Blood of Christ. Instituted following the establishment of the feast by Pope Urban IV in 1264, these processions feature the priest carrying the Eucharist in a monstrance under a canopy (known as an ombrellino or baldachin), accompanied by altar servers, religious, and the faithful. Elaborate local customs have developed: in many European countries, the route is adorned with flower carpets (infiorata in Italy, alfombras in Latin America), temporary outdoor altars are erected at four stations for Benediction and Gospel readings, and children scatter flower petals before the Blessed Sacrament. In some German-speaking regions, the processions travel by boat across lakes. These processions are among the most dramatic public expressions of Catholic belief in the Real Presence.",
