    oneLiner: "Prayers taught by the Angel of Portugal to the three Fatima children in 1916, emphasizing adoration, reparation, and Eucharistic devotion.",
    body: "In 1916, the year before the Marian apparitions at Fatima, an angel identifying himself as the Angel of Peace (also called the Angel of Portugal) appeared three times to the shepherd children Lucia, Francisco, and Jacinta. In the first apparition, the angel taught them a prayer of adoration: 'My God, I believe, I adore, I hope, and I love You. I ask pardon for those who do not believe, do not adore, do not hope, and do not love You.' In the third apparition, the angel appeared holding a chalice with a Host above it, from which drops of Blood fell into the chalice. He prostrated himself and taught a Trinitarian prayer of reparation before giving Holy Communion to the children. These prayers, though brief, are theologically rich — encompassing the theological virtues of faith, hope, and charity, along with the spirit of reparation that would become central to the Fatima message.",
    example: "Many Catholic families incorporate the Angel of Peace prayers into their daily routine, particularly before meals or during Eucharistic Adoration. The prostration of the angel has also inspired the practice of praying face-down before the Blessed Sacrament as an act of profound adoration.",
    whyItMatters: "The Angel of Peace prayers prepare the soul for deeper encounter with God by cultivating adoration, reparation, and the theological virtues. They remind Catholics that even angels worship the Eucharist and that reparation for the sins of unbelief is an urgent task for the faithful.",
