    oneLiner: "Devotion to the universal kingship of Jesus Christ over all nations, societies, and individual hearts, proclaimed by Pius XI in 1925.",
    body: "The devotion to Christ the King was given powerful liturgical expression when Pope Pius XI established the Feast of Christ the King in his 1925 encyclical Quas Primas. Writing in the aftermath of World War I and the rise of secularism, Pius XI declared that Christ's kingship extends not only over individuals and families but over civil societies and nations. The devotion affirms that no area of human life — politics, economics, culture, education — lies outside the rightful sovereignty of Christ. Quas Primas called for an annual renewal of the consecration of the human race to the Sacred Heart on the feast day. The feast was originally placed on the last Sunday of October but was moved to the last Sunday of the liturgical year after Vatican II, emphasizing that Christ's kingship will be fully revealed at the end of time. The devotion is expressed through acts of consecration, public processions, and the enthronement of Christ's image in homes and public buildings.",
    example: "On the Solemnity of Christ the King, many parishes pray the Act of Consecration of the Human Race to the Sacred Heart of Jesus, acknowledging: 'You are the King of all those who are still involved in the darkness of idolatry or of Islam; refuse not to draw them all into the light and kingdom of God.'",
