    oneLiner: "The practice of formal evening prayers before sleep, commending oneself to God's protection through the night.",
    body: "Night Prayers (also known as bedtime prayers or evening devotions) is the ancient Catholic practice of concluding the day with prayer before sleep. The liturgical form is Compline (Night Prayer from the Liturgy of the Hours), the Church's official night prayer, which includes a brief examination of conscience, a hymn, a psalm, the Nunc Dimittis (Simeon's canticle), and the final antiphon to Our Lady. Beyond Compline, traditional night prayer devotions include the Act of Contrition, prayers to one's guardian angel, the prayer to St. Michael the Archangel, commending one's soul to God ('Into Your hands, O Lord, I commend my spirit'), and sprinkling oneself with holy water. The Catholic tradition of night prayer is built on the awareness that sleep is an image of death — each night we entrust ourselves to God not knowing if we shall wake, and so we prepare our souls as we would for judgment.",
    example: "A Catholic family gathers at the children's bedside each night. They pray an Act of Contrition together, ask their guardian angels for protection, and the parents trace the sign of the cross on each child's forehead with holy water, saying: 'May almighty God bless you and keep you through this night.'",
    whyItMatters: "Night Prayers sanctify the transition from waking to sleep, the most vulnerable moment of the day. By consciously entrusting oneself to God at day's end, the faithful practice the ultimate act of trust — surrendering consciousness itself — and cultivate readiness for the final sleep of death.",
