    oneLiner: "A neighborhood-based practice of rotating the Rosary from home to home, bringing Marian prayer and community building to city blocks.",
    body: "The Block Rosary is a grassroots devotional practice in which Catholic families on the same street or neighborhood take turns hosting the Rosary in their homes on a rotating basis, typically weekly or monthly. The practice originated in Ireland and became closely associated with the Legion of Mary, which promoted it as a means of evangelization and community building. A statue of Our Lady is carried from home to home along with the rosary group. The host family prepares a small prayer space, and neighbors gather for the Rosary followed by brief fellowship. The Block Rosary has been credited with converting non-practicing Catholics, healing neighborhood tensions, and forming strong parish communities. In the Philippines, where the practice is especially popular, Block Rosary groups number in the thousands and often continue for decades, becoming integral to neighborhood identity.",
    example: "Every Tuesday evening, a statue of Our Lady visits a different home on Maple Street. The host family places the statue on a table with candles and flowers. Eight to twelve neighbors gather, pray five decades of the Rosary, and share tea afterward. The statue moves to the next house the following week.",
    whyItMatters: "The Block Rosary brings prayer out of the church and into the neighborhood, making the faith visible and communal at the most local level. It evangelizes through hospitality and presence, building bonds of charity among neighbors while placing the entire area under Mary's protection.",
    relatedTerms: ["devotions-rosary", "devotions-family-rosary", "devotions-living-rosary", "devotions-confraternities"]
